<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-668-816  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 668 816.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 18 1989 v6 n37 p41(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Packet-switching ability added to cisco's X.25 network routers.andO;(cisco Systems Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miles, J.B.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Cisco Systems Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     EnhancementsX.25 ProtocolTelecommunicationsSoftware packagesTransmission Control Protocol-Internet Protocol (Computer NetworkProtocol)Switches.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By J.B.andP;  MilesandM;cisco Systems Inc. is planning to add X.25 packet-switching capabilities toits existing X.25 routing software, enabling its internetwork routers toserve double duty as X.25 packet switches.andM;The new packet-switching capability also will allow cisco's customers tomonitor both X.25 and TCP/IP networks with a single, integratednetwork-management system, said John Morgridge, president of the Menlo Park,Calif., company.andM;Beginning next month, cisco will add the packet-switching feature to the X.25protocol software, which it sells as an option to its network routers for$1,200 or higher, depending on the router used, according to Morgridge.andM;With the new software, cisco routers will be able to function as X.25routers, which pass data between networks, or as X.25 packet switches forconnecting directly to standard X.25 devices or switching X.25 packets overmultiple synchronous lines.andM;The new cisco switches will offer transmission rates as fast as 4M bps, whichis up to 60 times the 64K-bps speed of conventional packet switches,according to Morgridge.andM;Because the software also will allow customers to combine X.25packet-switching networks with existing networks that use industry-standardTCP/IP communications protocols, users will be able to eliminate separateTCP/ IP and X.25 management systems, he added.andM;&quot;More and more organizations are building large, enterprisewide networks byusing standard protocols such as TCP/IP to connect their high-speed LANs,&quot;Morgridge explained.andM;&quot;But many such installations already have X.25 devices that could notpreviously be integrated with such a WAN.&quot;andM;The new software rounds out cisco's product line for integrating local andwide area networks.andP;  That line includes a family of X.25 packetassembler/disassemblers, internetwork routers using X.25 as the transportmedium and X.25-to-TCP/IP protocol translators.andM;cisco Systems Inc. can be reached at (415) 326-1941.andO;</TEXT></DOC>